QUINT escaped the sharks in 1945, but they finally catch up to him. Quint's death is the last one in the movie, and the most prolonged and graphic. In the book, Quint is accidentally dragged by a harpoon rope into the water and drowned (just like Ahab in Moby Dick). Spielberg thought that wasn't dramatic enough\u2014thus the more Jaws-y movie death, as he slowly slides down toward the shark's snapping jaws and is bitten in half as he desperately stabs the shark and tries to fight it off. As Quint screams in terror and agony, we can't help but think about how he cheated death after the USS Indianapolis incident but succumbed in the end. It's much more tragic than if he had just drowned. DO YOU THINK IT WAS QUINT\u2019S DESTINY TO MEET HIS FATE AT THE HANDS, OR MOUTH, OF JAWS? Player Profile

Byron Murphy, CB, Washington

Position Rank, # 1

Byron Murphy is a fearless cornerback who hails from a school that has put out many big time players in the secondary over the years. He can play man, zone, and is fearless in the run game. He is an extreme competitor who is constantly searching for a way to make a big play. 
Pros:
- High motor/effort guy
-Sticky in coverage and seems to get under receivers skin
-Great ball skills, had 7 interception and 20 pass break ups in 2 years with the huskies
-Accounted for 58 tackles this year, the NFL values comets who tackle tremendously - Has decent size, just could stand to add some muscle
-Intelligent player who has great instincts at the cornerback position 
Cons:
-Lacks a great height weight speed combination but makes up for it with instincts and a high motor
-Somewhat unexperienced, only played 2 seasons

“How do a doctor and a teacher meet anyway?”
.
.
2 years later and we still can’t help but smile and give a little laugh. Our story isn’t like most.
.
.

.
The last thing I expected was to meet a man who dreams of becoming a doctor that will help people just like my father. Someone who’s passion lies in the brain.
.
.
I tell people our story and I get a mixture of emotions: a lot of tears, a lot of smiles... but my favorite by far is this:
“Your dad was looking down at you... it’s no coincidence you were sat next to Justin that night.”
.
.

You want a guy who can go out and catch the ball,\u201d said Foles. \u201cI\u2019ve played with two of the best in the game: Travis Kelce and Zach Ertz. I\u2019ve also played with a young up and comer in Dallas Goedert as well as Brent Celek. It\u2019s really important. You have to be able to run the ball with a tight end in the game, but they also have to be able to catch the ball. On this day in Telephone History, October 14TH, 1930
Indiana Bell Telephone moved their 11,000 ton, eight story telephone building, 52 feet south, rotated it to face a new direction, and then moved it 100 feet west, without interrupting telephone service! (GTFO). The move was completed on November 12TH.

Throwback to our first spring in southern Indiana. My daughter and I took our foster dog, Jake, for a hike along German Ridge in the Hoosier National Forest. Along the way, three small puppies approached and followed us for two miles to our vehicle. We loaded them up and stopped at the house nearest to where they\u2019d appeared. A man there said they\u2019d belonged to him, their mother had been killed, and they were in need of homes. I took all three. A rescue group run by a friend took two and we kept the third, the smallest and most timid of the group. We named her Lily. She was 7 in December."

Thanks to my training partners @husseyjd And @katyz37 (Who also won her division)
